Loan Data¶

The dataset in hand contains the relevant information of 113,937 loans isseued between 2005 and 2014.

Let's limit our investigation to the most interesting variables and how they relate to one another¶

Our Variables of interest would be:¶

  • CreditGrade / CreditScoreRangeLower / CreditScoreRangeUpper
  • Term
  • LoanStatus (Target)
  • BorrowerAPR
  • BorrowerRate
  • ProsperScore (risk score)
  • IncomeRange
  • Recommendations
  • Investors
  • LoanOriginalAmount

Our objective will be studying what affects the APR and the LoanStatus (being complete or not)

Let's try plotting relative frequencies instead
First we need to calculate and store them

In [45]:
# Will need this throughout
def relative_freq_loanstat(col, sort=True):
    
    loan_status=df.LoanStatus.unique()
    loan_status=loan_status[loan_status != 'Current'] # We are not currrently interesrted in current loans
    
    unique_values=df[col].unique()
    unique_values=unique_values[~np.isnan(unique_values)]
    if sort:
        unique_values=np.sort(unique_values)
    status_df = pd.DataFrame(index=unique_values, columns=loan_status)
    
    for value in unique_values:
        for stat in loan_status:
            total_count=df.loc[(df[col] == value) & (df.LoanStatus != 'Current')].shape[0]
            if total_count>0:
                rel_freq= df.loc[(df[col] == value)&(df.LoanStatus == stat)].shape[0]/ total_count
            else:
                rel_freq=0
            status_df.loc[value, stat] = rel_freq
    return status_df
In [46]:
status_score=relative_freq_loanstat('CreditScoreRangeUpper')
In [47]:
status_score[status_score.index>400].plot(kind='bar');

Very SMOOTH.
As expected the relative frequency of charged off and defaulted goes down as the credit score increases while the percentage of completed loans goes up
However, we cannot see any information about 'Past Due' Loans as they are apparently very rare.
Let's have a closer look we expect they should also decrease in frequency with the increase in credit scores.

In [48]:
status_score['Past Due'].plot(kind='bar');

Very Suspicious plot here. Quite clearly the percentage of past due loans is very low and we couldn't have inferred that much from this plot anyways. Apparently due to randomness(very small sample size) we are having this counter-intuitive plot up there where past due loans go up with the increasing of the credit score and start to go down at a credit score of 679

Let is see if we can infer any relationship between the length of the loan and its completness
We would follow the same steps as before calculating relative frequencies
